                            <body>
                                <p> MANILA, Sept 23 (Reuters) - The Philippine Supreme Court  rejected on Monday a petition by 30 convicts to stop their  executions while Congress was debating a proposal to abolish  capital punishment.</p>
                                <p> But the court threw the fate of the convicts -- including  20 rapists -- into the lap of President Gloria Macapagal  Arroyo, saying she still had the power to pardon them.</p>
                                <p> A lawyers' group filed the petition for the convicts last  month on the grounds that the legislature was debating a bill  to scrap the death penalty in the largely Roman Catholic  country.</p>
                                <p> The court, by a 14-0 vote, rejected the argument as  speculative.</p>
                                <p> "While newspaper reports indicate the supposed acquiescence  of a number of senators and congressmen to the abolition of the  death penalty, such is by no means an assurance that these same  legislators will eventually vote for the modification or repeal  of the law," the court said.</p>
                                <p> "In the meantime, perhaps the remedy lies not in the  Supreme Court but in the Office of the President, to which any  plea for reprieve (or even pardon) ought to be properly  addressed."     Arroyo, a staunch Catholic, last month ordered  a 90-day reprieve for three rapists facing imminent execution  and drew immediate fire from anti-crime watchdogs, who said  executions would curb growing lawlessness in the country.</p>
                                <p> The Philippines has executed seven convicts since it  restored the death penalty in 1994. More than 1,000 people are  now on death row, including 29 women.</p>
                                <p> A group of legislators opposed to capital punishment say  it   does not deter crime and that many of those sentenced to death  are poor, illiterate people who cannot afford a good lawyer.</p>
                                <p> Under Philippine law, all death sentences imposed by trial  courts must be reviewed by the Supreme Court.    </p>
